Tuesday, May 02, 2017

Introduction

  • Analysis and comprehension of high-throughput -omics data
  • Started in 2002
  • 1383 software packages
  • 43,000 unique downloads per month
  • 10,600 mentions in PubmedCentral, 22,800 citations of Bioconductor packages
  • Most recent marker manuscript (Huber et al. 2015) with 350 citations
  • Highly respected–Nature Genetics, Credit for Code

About

The Bioconductor Environment

Built on the R statistical programming environment

  • Intrinsically statistical and quantitative nature of data
  • Allows flexibility to code new solutions
  • Supports modular packages with high-level functions encapsulating complex analytical methods
  • Analysis built as a set of "scripts" or other text files, so intrinsically reproducible
  • Also supports graphical interfaces for easier usage by non-programmers

R itself is:

  • Free
  • Open source and open development
  • Used by millions

The Bioconductor Project

Three main components:

  • A set of values and mission
    • Reproducible computational research
    • Statistical rigor
    • A community-based, open development model
    • Education and training
  • A repository and infrastructure supporting software development and distribution
  • An active user and developer community
    • https://support.bioconductor.org with about 8,000 contributors, more than 100 Q/A per month
    • 900+ developers (on mailing list)

The Analytical Domains of Bioconductor

  • Microarrays: gene expression, copy number, methylation, tiling arrays, snp genotyping
  • Sequencing:
    • RNA-seq: normalization, quality control, differential gene expression, isoform expression, gene networks, pathway analysis, fusion genes, single-cell
    • DNA-seq: variant cataloging, variant annotation, integration with epigenomics, exploratory data analysis
    • ChIP-seq: genomic region mining, quality control, differential binding, plotting
    • Others: DNAse-seq, FAIRE, 3D-conformation assays, methylseq, structural variation, …
  • Others: flow cytometry, mass spec, microbiome/metagenomics, proteomics, metabolomics

Bioconductor: Built on R

x = rnorm(100)
y = x + rnorm(100,sd=1)
df = data.frame(X = x, Y = y)
fit = lm( Y ~ X , data = df)
anova(fit)

Omics Workflows

Bioconductor: A Skeleton RNA-seq Workflow

Inputs needed:

  • description of experimental design
  • summary of read counts per gene
assay <- read.table("assay.tab") # Plain text files
pdata <- read.table("pdata.tab")
library(DESeq2)
dds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(assay, pdata, ~ cell + dex)
result(DESeq(dds))

Output: Table of differentially expressed genes, log fold change, adjusted P-value, etc.
